---
// Corrections log (EN — primary for the global audience; KO twin at /corrections/).
// Policy + incident report + auto-generated list of corrected EN posts (frontmatter `updated`).
// Trust principle: corrections are never hidden — same URL, visible notice, dateModified, listed here.
import { getCollection } from 'astro:content';
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';

const cols = ['track-record', 'market', 'spotlight', 'journal'] as const;
let corrected: any[] = [];
for (const c of cols) {
  const e = await getCollection(c, ({ data }) => !data.draft && data.updated);
  corrected.push(...e.map((x) => ({ ...x, _collection: c })));
}
corrected.sort((a, b) => (b.data.date.valueOf() - a.data.date.valueOf()));
const enPosts = corrected.filter((p) => p.data.lang === 'en');
const fmt = (d: Date) => d.toISOString().slice(0, 10);
---
<BaseLayout title="Corrections — OneQAZ" description="OneQAZ corrections log — every corrected post, with the reason, timeline, and safeguards. We do not silently rewrite history." lang="en">
  <link rel="alternate" hreflang="en" href="https://blog.oneqaz.com/en/corrections/" slot="head" />
  <link rel="alternate" hreflang="ko" href="https://blog.oneqaz.com/corrections/" slot="head" />
  <link rel="alternate" hreflang="x-default" href="https://blog.oneqaz.com/en/corrections/" slot="head" />
  <article class="container post">
    <p class="eyebrow">corrections <a class="lt" href="/corrections/">한국어</a></p>
    <h1>Corrections</h1>
    <p class="muted lede">
      OneQAZ aims to be a verifiable, timestamped record. When we find an error we
      <strong>never hide it or silently overwrite it</strong> — the post is republished at the same
      URL with a visible correction notice and a modification timestamp (dateModified), and the
      reason is disclosed on this page.
    </p>

    <h2>Incident report: the 2026-07 simulation-data defect</h2>
    <p>
      <strong>What happened.</strong> Between 2026-07-08 and 07-15, a signal-persistence fault in
      the trading engine caused new simulated entries to be recorded at <strong>stale signal prices
      from days earlier</strong> instead of live market prices. Exits were still evaluated at
      real-time prices, so the ledger filled with simulated trades at prices — and returns
      (±10–35%) — that could not exist in the actual market, and the same fault kept re-buying at
      identical prices in a loop. Roughly <strong>79% of closed trades in that window</strong> were
      such artifacts.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Impact on this blog.</strong> Daily journals aggregate the ledger as-is, so the fake
      trades surfaced in that window's journals (three markets) and one weekly track record.
      Separately, an internal test symbol (TEST) leaked one row into the 07-07 crypto journal.
    </p>
    <p><strong>Response timeline (KST).</strong></p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>07-15 21:00</strong> — four root-cause fixes applied to the engine and restarted
        (live-price validation on entries, signal-freshness gate, and others).</li>
      <li><strong>07-16 early AM</strong> — defective trades <strong>quarantined</strong> in the
        ledger (moved aside, not deleted — auditability preserved).</li>
      <li><strong>07-16</strong> — affected posts corrected and republished (first pass), each with
        a top-of-post notice and dateModified.</li>
      <li><strong>07-16~17</strong> — <strong>second-pass correction</strong>: we found and fixed a
        defect in our own first pass. The data view used for re-querying only covers a rolling
        7-day window, so some republished posts covering older windows were rebuilt with zero or
        partial counts. We re-queried the full-history source and corrected them again with the
        real figures (e.g. 243 crypto trades on 07-08). That mistake is kept on the record too.</li>
      <li><strong>07-17</strong> — <strong>full audit of the publication history</strong> (67 daily
        journals + 4 track records) against the ledger: zero mismatches, zero further defects.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      <strong>Preventing recurrence.</strong> ① Two automatic publish-time sanity checks — a
      repeated-identical-entry-price pattern, or a spike in ultra-short extreme-P&L trades, holds
      publication and alerts the operator (if upstream data is ever contaminated again, the blog is
      the last line of defense). ② Non-tradable symbols are excluded automatically. ③ The
      prediction ledger is sealed by a daily SHA-256 hash chain (anchor published in weekly track
      records), so any post-hoc edit shows up as a chain mismatch.
    </p>

    <h2>Corrected posts <span class="count">({enPosts.length} · auto-generated)</span></h2>
    <p class="muted small">Any post with a correction timestamp (updated) in its frontmatter is
      listed here automatically. Original URLs never change. Korean-language corrections are listed
      on the <a href="/corrections/">Korean page</a>.</p>
    <ul class="list">
      {enPosts.map((p) => (
        <li>
          <a href={`/${p._collection}/${p.slug}/`}>{p.data.title}</a>
          <span class="muted"> — published {fmt(p.data.date)} · corrected {fmt(p.data.updated)}</span>
        </li>
      ))}
    </ul>
  </article>
</BaseLayout>

<style>
  .post { padding: 56px 24px 80px; }
  h1 { font-size: clamp(26px, 4vw, 38px); font-weight: 700; color: var(--text); margin: 8px 0 14px; }
  h2 { font-size: 21px; font-weight: 600; margin: 40px 0 14px; color: var(--text); }
  .lede { font-size: 14px; line-height: 1.8; max-width: 640px; }
  p, li { font-size: 14px; line-height: 1.8; color: var(--text); }
  p { margin: 0 0 16px; }
  ul { margin: 0 0 16px 22px; }
  li { margin: 6px 0; }
  .count { font-size: 13px; font-weight: 400; color: var(--text-muted); }
  .small { font-size: 12px; }
  .list { list-style: none; margin-left: 0; }
  .list li { border-bottom: 1px solid color-mix(in srgb, var(--border) 55%, transparent); padding: 8px 0; }
  .list a { color: var(--amber); }
  .lt { margin-left: 10px; font-size: 11px; padding: 2px 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border); border-radius: 999px; color: var(--text-muted); letter-spacing: .5px; }
</style>
